ETHERNET CABLE VS FIBER OPTIC CABLE

|      Feature        |                         Ethernet Cable                                 |                               Fiber Optic Cable                                        |
|---------------------|------------------------------------------------------------------------|----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------|
| Transmission Medium | Uses electrical signals through copper wires.                          | Uses pulses of light through glass or plastic fibers.                                  |
| Speed & Distance    | Suitable for short distances (up to about 100 meters) with high speeds.| Supports much higher speeds over very long distances (several kilometers).             |
| Interference        | Can be affected by electromagnetic interference (EMI).                 | Immune to electromagnetic interference, making it more reliable in noisy environments. |

Real-World Examples:

1. Ethernet Cable
   - Example: Used to connect a home Wi-Fi router to a desktop PC, gaming console, or smart TV.

2. Fiber Optic Cable
   - Example: Used for data center connections, Internet Service Provider (ISP) backbone networks, and college campus backbone networks to provide high-speed internet over long distances.
